      "[\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Presenter Speech\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Michael Queen\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Thanks, Patrick. Good morning, everyone, and welcome to our Half Yearly Results Presentation. This is our agenda for today. I'm going to give a short introduction, and then Julia will present a financial review of the first half year. Cressida Hogg, who's our managing partner of the Infrastructure business, will then give you an overview of this important part of 3i's investment activity. And finally, I'll review our strategic progress and cover the outlook and priorities for the next six months.\\nAs I said in the statement this morning, we've increased momentum throughout the business. Our portfolio has delivered a good performance, achieving a gross portfolio return of 8.7% for the six months to the 30th of September. Total return was lower at 3.8%, although NAV growth over the last 12 months is over 15%. We've made good progress in terms of strategic development, and we now have three strong platforms for growth. \\nIn the last few presentations to you, I've talked about planning and organizing for growth. We've now moved into the delivery phase. And I'll give you more detail on this later. \\nBut before that, Julia will review our financial performance.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Presenter Speech\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Julia Wilson\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Thank you, Michael, and good morning, everybody. \\nLet me start my financial update by taking you through the highlights of the six months to September. \\nInvestment at GBP 327 million was still at a relatively modest level, although significantly up from last year. Our portfolio has performed well, with an improvement in earnings evaluation purposes of 8% in the six months. This is a key driver of the 8.7% gross portfolio return in the six months, despite lower multiples used to value the portfolio.\\nThe benefits of the tough decisions we've taken in our own business is reflected in our operating costs, which have continued to fall. Our total return on opening shareholders funds at 3.8% was an encouraging result. And consequently, the board has approved an interim dividend of 1.2p per share, as we've taken the opportunity to reset our dividend at a higher lever.\\nNAV per share grew by 9p in the period to 3.30p. Importantly, as Michael said, this is a 15% increase on a year ago. And we have finished the period with liquidity of more than GBP 2 billion and net debt of only GBP 352 million.\\nLet me give you some more detail on the investment of GBP 327 million. We have invested GBP 58 million in two new businesses: , which is a European calibration service provider; and Vedici, the fifth-largest acute healthcare company in France. In this very competitive market, both experience and will provide opportunities to buy and build. \\nMore than a third investment was made expanding the investment in our existing portfolio. We continue to provide acquisition funding as we see our portfolio companies able to transactions which are not subject to the same high prices we see elsewhere. And we've also taken the opportunity in two cases to buy senior debt and pick at discounted value is.\\nRealizations of GBP 293 million were achieved as an 11% uplift over opening book value. The most significant individual transaction was the sale of its global Commodity Testing and Inspection division. As a result, we received proceeds of GBP 121 million and retained a top 30 investment, which is valued at GBP 42 million, which is now called ESG and is focused on environmental and food testing.\\nDespite the prevalence of secondary transactions in the market, almost all of our realizations with the non-financial buyers.\\nLooking on at the breakdown of our total return. Gross portfolio return is the return we generate directly from our portfolio. The GBP 307 million represents an 8.7% return on opening portfolio value for the six-month period. It is driven by period performance in the portfolio, giving unrealized profits of GBP 196 million. All our core business lines generated an 8% return in the six-month period.\\nWe then get to net portfolio return reflecting the income across associated with Asset Management business. For GBP 206 million represent the gross portfolio return diluted by carry payable and operating expenses and enhanced by carry receivable and fund fee income.\\nFinally, total return takes account of the effects of our balance sheet structure. So the GBP 117 million of return is achieved after deducting of cost of finance as well as a net exchange loss of GBP 29 million.\\nSo turning then to the valuation of our portfolio and its effect on our returns in the period. You will see from this slide that most of the return in this period comes from the highest-quality factors, uplifts to sale and portfolio earnings growth. This builds on the momentum in the second half of last year and represents a very different picture from that of 12 months ago. \\nThe uplift on assets which are in the process of being sold was GBP 66 million in the six-month period. It includes the sale to Caterpillar of MWM, what is a German-headquartered global business supplying alternative engines. This transaction is expected is complete by the end of the year.\\nSo this slide gives you some more detail on the earnings and multiple movements that we've used in our valuations exercise. As I've said before, the most striking aspect is the improvement in the quality of value growth. \\nLooking at the first line in the table, earnings used for the valuations grew by 8% in the first half, accounting for GBP 273 million of growth. This followed the 5% increase in the second half of last year and compared to the 13% decrease in the comparative period. This growth reflects the tough actions that our portfolio companies have been taking in the face of the considerable economic uncertainty that Michael has talked about in his statement this morning.\\nMarkets were volatile in the six months. And overall, the market month pulls in the sectors and geographies in which we are invested fell during the period. Consequently, the multiples we used in the valuations declined by 5%. This compares to a 10% increase in the second half of last year and a 21% increase in the comparative period. As usual, we've provided you with further analysis regarding our valuations in the appendices to your presentation.\\nBefore talking about the balance sheet, let me make a few comments on other components of total return. Fund fee income generated is marginally up on the same period last year. This is principally due to capital funded the end of March. As I mentioned earlier, we have taken tough actions ourselves to improve cost efficiency. Operating costs were down to GBP 89 million for the six-month period. I do expect us to be marginally higher in the second half although the year-on-year trajectory remains down. \\nThe GBP 29 million exchange loss was incurred in the first six months due to the strengthening of sterling. The earning hedging in operation in the six-month period was affected by our core currency borrowings. As we've noted in our statement this morning, the board has recently decided to extend the hedging policy to include the use of derivatives. This is a limited extension and will not exceed 30% of the corresponding portfolio value. Implementation will be phased throughout the second half of this year.\\nTurning then to the balance sheet. We've continued to adopt a conservative approach to our balance sheet management. We set ourselves a limit on net debt of GBP 1 billion. We have also objective of reducing our gross debt and managing maturities so that over time, maturities in any one year will be no more than the GBP 300 million. Consistent with our strategy, gross debt has been reduced by GBP 354 million through a series of actions, significantly, the repayments of GBP 195 million of the convertible bond and GBP 89 million of commercial paper. And we've continued the this activity until September. \\nThere was an increase in net debt in as a result of net cash outflow in the period due to operating activity. However, the net debt GBP 352 million is comfortable within our GBP 1 million limit. And the group's liquidity position remains very strong at GBP 2.1 billion, meaning, we are well positioned for investment.\\nSo in summary and to complete my review of the financial performance, we have seen good portfolio performance, driven by earnings improvements. We have a continued focus on conservative balance sheet management, and we remain well positioned to manage against continuing uncertainty in the market and take advantage of investment opportunities.\\nThank you. I'm now going to hand over to Cressida who's going to update you on our Infrastructure business.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Presenter Speech\",\n",
