      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Presenter Speech\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Michael Queen\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Thanks, Cressida. I'd now like to update you on our strategic progress and then talk about the outlook on our priorities for the second half. \\nThe four quarter elements of our strategy, as set out on the slide, are also described in detail on our IR website as well as in our annual report. And today, I want to mainly focus on two aspects of this strategy, investing and growing the business. \\nLet me start with investment. High-quality new investment is important to future value growth. But the environment for making good investments has been challenging. Let me explain what I mean by challenging. Volume of private equity activity across Europe has been very low. The number of transactions for both growth and buyouts is a third the level than it was in 2007. But the funds available for investment continue to be very high, with the consequence that most transactions in Europe have been very at high prices so we have an overhang of capital in our industry.\\nNow in this environment, we've taking a measured and highly selective approach to the market and focused only on making investments where we feel we can make a significant impact on the performance of a particular company. \\nTrescal is a very good example of such a situation. It's a classic mid-market buyout in terms of size and profile. Trescal is a French-based International business, providing calibration services for a wide range of industrial companies. It has revenue of EUR 110 million and operates 60 laboratories in 11 countries. We were able to invest through our strong relationship with the management, our experience having made several successful investments in the sector and the involvement of from our business leaders network. \\nThe investment case is based on four components. Firstly, Trescal is in a growing sector, as many of its customers are looking to outsource testing and measurement. Secondly, because capital investment is required in building a company like Trescal, there are significant barriers to entry. Thirdly, through our active partnership analysis, we and management believe there's considerable opportunity for operational improvement. And finally, given its market position and a highly fragmented sector, there's a real opportunity for buy and build.\\nNow increasing the level of investment is only one way to grow 3i's value. In addition, we must also continue to take every opportunity to grow the value of our existing portfolio. Earnings growth in our portfolio is being good. And one of the ways that our portfolio companies have been delivering this is to find opportunities in developing markets. \\nMWM is a very good example of this. MWM is a GBP 360 million euro buyout from Deutsche AG 2007. And it's a leading manufacturer of engines that are used to produce power. Now a typical use for an MWM engine is generating power from landfill gas sites, so there's huge demand for these products in the developing world.\\nOur investment case was based on growth and significant operational improvement. And key to delivering this was the introduction of Peter, again from 3i's Business Leaders Network to lead a program of significant cultural change, alongside a number of 3i active partnership initiatives to improve MWM's strategic position and operational effectiveness.\\nPerformance of the business has dramatically improved, and its market position is being strengthened. And this made it a really attractive acquisition target. And last month, we announced that Caterpillar had agreed to purchase MWM for EUR 580 million. Now this sale which is subject to various regulatory approvals will deliver 2.2x money multiple and proceeds of EUR 224 million to 3i Group, as well as on an IRR of 25% for 3i and the investors in our Eurofund V.\\nIn addition to making high-quality investments such as Trescal and MWM and doing everything we can to help these businesses grow their earnings and improve their strategic positioning, we've also been investing in 3i itself. Our Infrastructure business is a great example of this. But another strategic investment is our Debt Management business. This started in 2005 with a small in-house team. The team provides banking expertise to our deal teams and to our portfolio. In addition, it invests in high-quality debt instruments in non-3i investments. This team's been a major source of strength to 3i throughout the credit crisis and has added considerable value to our investment teams and our portfolio of companies. Given this positive experience, we saw a real strategic opportunity to expand our debt investment and management activities.\\nThe acquisition of MIM or was therefore an actual step. MIM manages GBP 3.7 billion of assets in eight funds of corporate, senior and subordinated debt. The rationale for the deal was straightforward. MIM builds on the 3i's existing debt management capabilities. MIM also brings an experienced team of 28 people to 3i, including Jeremy. Jeremy will join our leadership team and head up the Debt Management business. This move creates a platform to manage multiple funds and provides the potential to diversify into other debt products, as well as the capacity to grow using 3i's balance sheet.\\nStrategically, the Debt Management business is important because like infrastructure, it provides the opportunity for a good source of low volatility returns with a significant yield component. \\nThis next slide shows you the shape of the business once the MIM acquisition is complete, which we expect to be at the end of January 2011. Our Private Equity business is clearly the largest, with assets under management of GBP 7.5 billion. \\nIn September, we announced the decision to combine our Buyout and Growth Capital businesses to form a single Private Equity business. The rationale for this change was to ensure that we had the right model for a changing market and is based on ensuring we continue to develop our business model to maintain a sustainable competitive advantage.\\nOur Buyout and Growth Capital businesses have the same mid-market focus, targeting companies with an enterprise value in the range of EUR 100 million to EUR 1 billion. They have the same investment and management processes, and our teams adopt the same approach to achieving influence through being active members of the portfolio company boards. They share the same active partnership approach to driving value, both use the group's network and next sector expertise and both draw on our Business Leaders Network members.\\nNow another important driver of this decision was our view on what the next generation of private equity funds might look like. Our view was that an evil vision towards more regionally-based funds and most LPs are more focused on making geographic allocations than the distinction between majority and minority private equity investments. \\nWe've also been preparing for the next generation of leadership in our investment business, and I'll say more on that in a minute.\\nThis change has been welcomed by professional advisors, management teams, our Business Leaders Network and our own people. The feedback that we've had is it will make 3i easier to understand and easier to deal with. And this is critical in a highly competitive market. We've been actively communicating with our LP investors in both our buyout and growth funds. And we are, of course, committed to managing these funds on the same basis through to the end of their investing periods. \\nNow following these changes, we're in a six-month consultation period with our Eurofund Advisory Board. Those discussions are constructive and include the possibility of potentially extending the fund for one year beyond November 2011. Notwithstanding the six-month consultation period, we expect matters to be resolved by the end of the calendar year. So the bottom line is the fund continues as normal.\\nWe've also recently promoted three people to the leadership team, Alan Giddins and Cressida Hogg, you already heard from. has been a senior partner in the Buyout business and will take over leadership of the buyout fund and the geographical responsibility for Northern Europe. Alan Giddins, who is also a senior partner in Buyouts and has also that our business services sector across the whole company, will have responsibility for the U.K. and all our sector activities. \\nWe now have three stroke platforms for growth, which can leverage our resources and expertise. The growth of our Debt Management and Infrastructure businesses brings similar benefits to 3i, not least in lowering potential volatility through generating increased revenue profits.\\nAnd I want to give you a brief update on six of our largest investments. There are some really common themes as to how they have generated growth and value in the recession. These are international development, improve strategy and positioning, operational effectiveness and also following a buy and build strategy. There more details of these and other companies in your packs and on the IR website. But let me to do so these companies. \\nACR is a pan-Asian reinsurer that we invested in, in 2006. Today, it has premiums of USD $500 million and customers across 50 countries. \\nis a leading manufacturer of joining technology products and solutions. It operates across 80 countries and, since we invested has opened new plants in China, Thailand, Mexico, Russia and Serbia. EBITDA has tripled during our investment period.\\nFoster & Partners is one of the world's most innovative architectural practices and since our investment has continued to expand internationally and has now deliver projects and 50 countries. EBITDA has grown 68% since our investment in 2007.\\nis a leading funeral service provider in Spain and Portugal. Through acquisitions, growth and operational improvement, EBITDA is up 21% from the time of our investment in 2008. \\nmay be well known to you through its brand. And this business has grown internationally from virtually nothing when we invested to 55% of sales today. \\nAnd the last of these six companies is, the global market leader in outsourced clinical trial. We've supported what was already an outstanding company to grow further in Asia and Europe. \\nBut let me return to the common themes. In five out of these six, we supported their international development. In all of them, our sector knowledge and ability to identify great people from our Business Leaders Network has either help the company directly or given 3i particular insight into the opportunities. In all of them, our active partnership initiative is generating operational improvements, improving their strategic positions and building robust growth through acquisitions that are enhancing returns. Together, these companies have a combined value of GBP 724 million. And more and more of our portfolio companies we're making these initiatives deliver value for us.\\nToday, we focus on the first two elements of our strategy, investing and growing 3i. In order to achieve these, it's absolutely critical that we do all that we can to ensure that 3i's reputation not only remains good, but that we build on it. \\nOur success internationally owes much to the strength of our brand. As you heard from Cressida, 3i's brand has been central to developing a strong position in the infrastructure market. 3i's repetition as a responsible investor is a core part of our brand and will be placing an increased emphasis on corporate responsibility, not just to the group level but also in all our portfolio companies.\\nAt our results presentation in May, I mentioned the One 3i approached that we've been driving the business. The point of this was to increase our effectiveness, especially in terms of how we source opportunities, how we convert these opportunities into investments and then how we create value once invested. This underpins all the other elements of our strategy. And of course, the real test of whether this strategy delivers value will be our long-term financial performance and reputation. \\nSo let me turn to the outlook and our priorities for the second half. Predicting the macroeconomic outlook remains a challenge. The important thing is that 3i is in a strong position to take advantage of either a sustained improvement or given our financial strength, to deal with further turbulence. \\nThe outlook for our Private Equity business is improving. Pricing will remain full. And I think that this will continue for another 12 to 18 months. But despite this, we can find good investments, as we've demonstrated with Trescal and Vedici. As Cressida said, conditions in the infrastructure market in Europe and in India look favorable. And as demonstrated by the two investments we've announced in the last week.\\nThe outlook for the Debt Management business is also positive, with the opportunity to grow assets under management through new funds and further acquisitions. The combination of the MIM team's track record and capabilities and 3i's brand and financial strength position us well to take advantage of these opportunities. \\nSo overall, the outlook for 3i is good, and we've therefore taken the opportunity to increase our dividend by 20%. In the short term, our priorities are to continue to deliver good financial performance, to integrate MIM, and to increase momentum in our investment activity. \\nSo in conclusion, our key themes for today are: we've increased the momentum throughout the business; our portfolio has also delivered a good performance; we've made good progress in terms of strategic development; and we now have three strong platforms for growth.\\nAs I also said at the beginning, we've moved from planning and organizing growth to delivering growth. \\nJulia, Cressida and I would now be happy to take any questions that you've got. [Operator Instructions]\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Question\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Christopher Brown\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Analysts\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Chris Brown from JPMorgan. Michael, you were talking about pricing remaining full. Can you talk about the prospects for upselling some assets into that strength in the second half? I mean, obviously, there have been a few press stories about one or two of your assets.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Michael Queen\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"I think we're learning to live with an environment where everything a financial company does is immediately reported in the press. So you have a pretty good view on the pipeline of potential realizations coming forward. What I can say is when we look at the assets that have been talked about, a number of our big industrial companies, particularly I think Continental Europe, we expect to achieve extremely attractive prices for these assets because they are really high quality businesses. One of the businesses that's being talked about that I referred to, , is just a sensational business. That has a potential to be a very, very strong IPO candidate,  not just a potential trade sale. It's a very attractive business. And the reason it's attractive is because it's got great exposure to developing markets. One of the things that we'd be pushing across all of our industrial portfolio is where they haven't already got strong market access in India, China or South America, really helping them to move that forward. And that's what make these assets very attractive. I mean, one of the things themes that we've been focused on is how do we access that developing market growth. And I think there are two ways to do that. One is to invest directly in Asian companies, which clearly we're doing as in GBK. But the other is to make sure our great European businesses are also accessing that growth, and therefore we can benefit in that one as well.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":null,\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":null,\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Securities. I've got a couple of questions. Firstly, provisions and impairments. These have increased again. I think over the last two halves, they were actually positive, if I remember correctly. Can you just give us a bit more color on that? How many assets are involved? And then the other question was on cash. I mean, there are quite a number of sales that have been announced over the last few months. If you project the cash that you're expecting to come in, how much is actually due to come in and be completed then leave net debt?\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Julia Wilson\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"So if I take your question on provisions and impairments, I mean, clearly, you're right. If you compare the numbers to last year, then it doesn't look like a particularly good shift. What it would say is clearly last year had almost the benefit of the previous year where we've had some very, very significant provisions and impairment. So I'd say last year was unusually low. And this year, the provision level is 1.1% of opening portfolio value. That's an unusual sort of amount. In terms of the underlying movement that's in there, it's a small number of assets. There's no particular themes that I can draw out for you that's spread across the business lines, that's spread across sectors and spread across geographies. The specific factors to particular investments and don't actually indicate any underlying trend the overall portfolio.And then in terms of cash for the period, I mean, clearly there are, as Michael has said, there was a number of transactions that are being well trailed in the market. We're not trying to give you a specific number where expect cash to be because we would like actually to be investing in the second half. So it's realistic to assume that there will be some significant realizations coming through. But in terms where net debt's going to be would be putting and some decent amount of investment in the second half. Some of that will come down to timing. Where we will talk about smaller numbers of large transactions, we can get quite different numbers coming over the year. So I would hope that we would have investment, but clearly number of realizations going through.\"\n",
      " },\n",
