      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Michael Queen\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Well, I think what we're looking to do overall is deliver 15% returns to shareholders. That will come in a combination of forms, will come from the earnings growth on the portfolio. We typically do see a step-up when we sell assets open above the carrying value, so that gives an additional boost to return; and of course, from the income streams from managing third-party assets, which clearly will start to rise as we incorporate the Debt Management business. I think if you look at this half year's performance, I mean, the way I try and look at this is to sort of x out multiple movement, both up and down, whether half-year period. And so I think what they're all about in terms of their consistency delivery with that delivery of that trend.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":null,\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":null,\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"From Merrill. Just kind of than note of leakage between net portfolio return and ultimate return. The net interest income was higher this half. In the statement, you talk about someone one-offs due to repurchase of bits and pieces of debt. Presumably,m those will improve the gross interest expense in future. Could you talk a little bit about the trajectory there please?\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Julia Wilson\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Yes. If I talk about the first half in particular, one other thing I talked about is the conservative balance sheet management and trying to extend our maturities and manage those maturities. So one of the factors that you have in this period is the consequence of us refinancing in affect the convertible bond ahead of time. So you remember we took advantage of the small of opportunity in March to raise the GBP 350 million fixed rate bond that we have. So you've got the interest cost of that coming, overlapping with the convertible bond in the period. It's a consequence of actually our conservative balance sheet management. The important thing is by next year, that overlap will have faded out. And then I don't really want to go to the joys of IS39 accounting. But one of the consequences of that in trying to manage the overlap I've talked about, we've been buying back our convertible bond in the market. The convertible bond has an amortization charge that comes through the total return statement. The consequence of buying it back early means that we've accelerated some of that amortization into the first half, so there's GBP 8 million of accelerated amortization sitting in those notes numbers. The way I'm looking at is really looking through to next year, when all of these factors should have washed out, when we'll have a fixed interest cost of about GBP 50 million. And that will be about half of our interest costs going forward.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":null,\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":null,\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"First, just following on the provisions and impairment side, am I right in the detail of the text you do highlighted help deterioration on the growth side of the portfolio, the percentage being done versus September versus March. I wonder what's going on there. And secondly, you mentioned about expectation of H2 OpEx being higher than H1. Could you give a bit color what's H1 or what's expected H2, given the H1 is strongly below the run rate, shall we say, of last year --\"\n",
