      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Julia Wilson\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Just with the OpEx point. Actually, some of our costs activity-related. So as activity levels are building up in terms of investment and improvement, then I'm expecting to see some cost coming through that. Effectively, what I'm saying to do is just don't double the number for the first half. There'll be a small increase on the first half. But overall, we're on a continuing downward trajectory.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Michael Queen\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"In terms of the health of the portfolio, I mean, the general trend actually is positive. We're seeing month by month continued overall trend. The provisions numbers are slightly skewed because you get an individual company that has got specific issues relating to that company that will go through the provision that will make a difference of that figure. So you can't necessarily draw conclusions across the portfolio from those individual numbers. One company in the growth portfolio that was a sizable chunk of that provision number, actually, could come back very strongly, so we could end up March actually in effect reversing out some of that provision. But we have a set policy that the company is performing a particularly way, we will make a provision. But the key message is the underlying health of the portfolio is continuing to show steady improvement.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":null,\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":null,\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Charles. Neiman Securities. Michael, I understand what you're saying about pricing. But even allowing for that, the level of investment growth in capital seems particularly low over the period. Were there any reasons for that? And how do you see that going forward?\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Michael Queen\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Charles, one of the things that we've always seen in this business going through economic cycles is that the demand for growth capital picks up as you start to come out of a downturn. So through the bottom of the market you don't actually see a lot of demand, and then you see that demand pick up. What's being unusual this time is as we've started to see economic recovery, there's been a real reticence among businesses to actually invest, whether it's in a fixed plant and equipment, going out and buying new businesses. Now it's hard to say whether that trend is going to continue. But it certainly surprised us that we haven't seen a stronger growth capital pickup, given where we are in the economic cycle. And it maybe that the way that the banks have behaved has resulted in people being extremely nervous about entering into any new commitments going forward. There is certainly an element of that. But I would have to say, I just think that this position, this growth in demand growth capital has simply been deferred. And certainly, if we look at the work in progress that we're seeing and we're tracking this on a daily basis, we are seeing the early stage work in progress around growth capital is starting to pick up. But I think it's too early to say whether that is an evidence of a trend. But I think it's being deferred in the cycle and certainly happening later than we saw in previous cycles.\"\n",
      " },\n",
      " {\n",
      "  \"transcriptcomponenttypename\":\"Answer\",\n",
      "  \"transcriptpersonname\":\"Michael Queen\",\n",
      "  \"companyofperson\":null,\n",
      "  \"speakertypename\":\"Executives\",\n",
      "  \"componenttext\":\"Well, if there aren't, as Patrick said, we wanted to conclude by 10:02. And amazingly, we've done exactly that. So thank you all very much for coming. \\nJulia, Cressida and I and Patrick are available all day for any other questions that you've got. And we look forward to seeing you over the next six months in our various one-on-one meetings. So thank you, all, for coming. Thank you.\"\n",
